Using beamforming to localize oscillatory power modulations

Table of Contents
Introduction Preparation Source modeling of modulations of alpha band activty Derive the spatial filters for the alpha band Plot the alpha modulation Question 1 Question 2 Source modeling of modulations of gamma band activty Derive the spatial filters for the gamma band Plot the gamma modulation Preregistration and publications References

Introduction

The aim of this section is to localize the modulations of oscillatory power. This will be done by using the Dynamical Imaging of Coherent Sources (DICS) approach (Gross et al, 2001). This is a beamforming methodology based on spatial filtering operating in the frequency domain. For each grid point in the brain, a spatial filter is derived based on the forward model and the cross-spectral density (CSD) matrix. A hanning taper for slower frequencies and multitaper approach for faster frequencies is applied for the spectral estimates. The approach allows for estimating the power modulations at each grid points which then is mapped onto the indiviual structural MRIs. We will localize oscillatory sources using gradiometers.

Preparation

Make sure FieldTrip is installed and path is set. Then run ft_defaults (only needs running once during each Matlab session).

The spatial filters in the DICS beamforming approach are calculated using the forward model and the cross-spectral density (CSD) matrices. We here focus on the -0.8 to -0.3 s interval prior to the onset of the gratings and the 0.3 to 0.8 s interval when the gratings are presented. During the presentation interval, the alpha band activity is suppressed (see the section Time-Frequency Representations of Power).
We start by calculating the CSDs for the 10 Hz alpha band for all conditions and the pre- and post-interval with applying a Hanning taper.
cfg = [];

cfg.method='mtmfft';
cfg.taper = 'hanning';
cfg.foi = 10;
freq_left_sh=ft_freqanalysis(cfg, data_left_sh);

Derive the spatial filters for the alpha band

For calculating the spatial filters we also need to derive the rank of the CSD. It will be similar to the the rank of the coveriance matrix. To do so first transform the cross-spectrum matrix into a square matrix format and then calculate the rank of the matrix. Note, this step is particularly important when MaxFilter has been applied to the data.
tmp_data = ft_checkdata(freq_sh_cmb, 'cmbstyle', 'full');
crss_rank=rank(tmp_data.crsspctrm);
Do the same for the 'attend left' and 'attend right' conditions combined with their baseline.
tmp_data = ft_checkdata(freq_sh_cmb_all, 'cmbstyle', 'full');
crss_rank_all=rank(tmp_data.crsspctrm);
Now calculate the filters using the previously calculated leadfield and headmodel, as well as the grad structure. For each source the orientation is optimized to maximize the power of the output. Given that the covariance matrix (or CSD) is severely rank-deficient due to the application of SSS and ICA, Fieldtrip will compute a pseudo-inverse using the rank calculated above ('cfg.dics.kappa'). Calculate the common spatial filter and then apply the attend left and attend right conditions.
cfg=[];
cfg.method='dics';
cfg.grad=grad;
cfg.frequency=freq_sh_cmb.freq;
cfg.sourcemodel=grid;
cfg.headmodel=headmodel;
cfg.dics.projectnoise='yes';
cfg.dics.keepfilter = 'yes';
cfg.dics.realfilter = 'yes';
cfg.dics.fixedori = 'yes';
cfg.dics.kappa=crss_rank;
source_cmb=ft_sourceanalysis(cfg,freq_sh_cmb);

Plot the alpha modulation

Calculate the relative change in power; i.e. the change in alpha power comparing the interval before and after the moving grating onset. Note that we are always comparing intervals or conditions in order to remove the depth bias confound:
source_con_all=source_left_all;
source_con_all.avg.pow=((source_left_all.avg.pow+source_right_all.avg.pow)-(source_left_bsl_all.avg.pow+source_right_bsl_all.avg.pow))./((source_left_bsl_all.avg.pow+source_right_bsl_all.avg.pow));

Calculate the CSD for the source localization with DICS beamforming. For this, we will apply the multitaper approach to ensure suffient spectral smoothing.
As a first step, calculate the CSD for the pre- and post-interval as well as all conditions. The bandwidth here is 2ΔF = 8 Hz and the time window ΔT = 0.475 s. This results in 3 tapers (as N < 2ΔF ΔT).
cfg = [];
cfg.output = 'powandcsd';
cfg.method = 'mtmfft';
cfg.taper = 'dpss';
cfg.foilim = [60 90];
cfg.tapsmofrq = 4;
cfg.keeptrials = 'no';
freq_high_left = ft_freqanalysis(cfg, data_gleft_sh);

Derive the spatial filters for the gamma band

The filters will be calculated on the basis of the common CSD. The rank estimate based on the covariance matrix will be used. The deduced rank is due to the SSS as well as the ICA.
tmp_data = ft_checkdata(freq_high_all, 'cmbstyle', 'full');
crss_rank_g=rank(tmp_data.crsspctrm);

cfg=[];

Plot the gamma modulation

Now calculate the relative modulation in gamma power with respect to the baseline:
Calculate the relative change in power; i.e. the change in alpha power comparing the interval before and after the moving grating onset. Note that we are always comparing intervals or conditions in order to remove the depth bias confound:
source_gcon_all=source_gleft;
source_gcon_all.avg.pow=((source_gleft.avg.pow+source_gright.avg.pow)-(source_gleft_bsl.avg.pow+source_gright_bsl.avg.pow))./((source_gleft_bsl.avg.pow+source_gright_bsl.avg.pow));
Interpolate the relative modulation on the MRI scan.
cfg=[];
cfg.parameter='avg.pow';
cfg.interpmethod ='nearest';
source_gconint=ft_sourceinterpolate(cfg,source_gcon_all,mri_realigned2);
Warning: use cfg.parameter='pow' instead of cfg.parameter='avg.pow'

Preregistration and publications

Example for text to be used for publications and preregistration:
"The Dynamics Imaging of Coherent Sources (DICSs) approach (Gross et al., 2001) was applied to localize the modulations of oscillatory brain activity. To localize the modulation in the alpha band, the cross-spectral density (CSD) was calculated for the 10 Hz activity using a multi-taper approach applying 2 Hz spectral smoothing. The CSD matrix was then calculated for the 300 - 800 ms stimulus interval in which the gratings were shown as well as the -800 – -300 ms pre-stimulus interval (using one Hanning taper). The combined CSD was used with the forward model to create a common spatial filter. This was done by first estimating the rank of the data (being reduced to ~70 due to the SSS and ICA approaches). The truncated pseudo-inverse was then calculated based on the estimated rank (Jas et al., 2018). For each source, the orientation was optimized to maximize the power of the output. The spatial filter was then applied to the CSDs to calculate the relative change in alpha power. As similar approach was used for the gamma band now considering the 60 - 90 Hz band and 8 Hz spectral smoothing (resulting in 3 DPSS tapers). The pre-stimulus time-interval was -0.6 to -0.125 s and the post-stimulus interval was 0.125 to 0.6 s. The source data were then mapped to the structural MRI. "

  • Engemann DA, Gramfort A. (2015) Automated model selection in covariance estimation and spatial whitening of MEG and EEG signals. Neuroimage 108:328-42.
